ну всяко лучше быдл с пивасами на уровне животных, которые пашут в диктатуре ради базовых физических потребностей таких как секс. ну и алкоголь, чтобы русскую тоску накрыть (вайб который с хрущевок в которых они живут). ловушка нищеты, и поделом вам, если первостепенно не духовенство, а низменные потребности. эпоха дворянства была нормальной только в россии, когда еще классики процветали, но и там было куча кутежов, а то что воспевали эти самые классики были лишь идиллическими образами (ну за исключением светского петербурга). И при Сталине было хорошо, в железных рукавицах держал этот народ, ну мы и видим как развивалась ссср - а сейчас что? сплошное разочарование и бесконечный цикл кредитов у 140 лямов. видите ли бухнуть и секса они хотят, уверен многие если даже не большинства рукоблуды (еще и дзюбу поливают грязью, жалкие), так как чтобы дала женщина нужно еще и заслужить, а рабы дофамина не многие могут, вот и накачивают гигабайтобороты порнхаба (глянь статистику посещения по сайтам, вероятно там немалые цифры, учитывая насколько Грей знают 90-е и нулевые, когда вся эта вертикаль власти и построилась)

A Coincidence with Spain : 
2010- They confirmed their tournament's termination at Soccer City, Johannesburg, South Africa which was 2010 World Cup final's venue 

2014-  They confirmed their tournament's termination at Marakana, Rio De Jenerio, Brazil which was 2014 World Cup final's venue . 

2018- They confirmed their tournament's termination at Luzniki , Moscow, Russia which was 2018 World Cup final's venue .

Difference is 2010 came to them with joy but 2014 and 2018 did that to them with grief .

author: @iSwearToCod

text: Hell yeah, of course we'd love it - everyone would. There's nothing weird about getting support from our American cousins and friends! You'd be treated like family. As you probably know, every two years there's a major international tournament (either the UEFA European Championship or the FIFA World Cup), and it brings us all together as a family, like nothing else quite can. This clip is from when we scored in the 2018 World Cup semi-final. It'd been the first time we'd reached that stage since 1990, and it was such a magical summer. Three years on, and we got to our first major final for 55 years - since we won the World Cup in '66! It was a spectacular run, and the whole nation was electric. It felt like 2018 again, and it was such an emotional release after the long, grim spectre of Covid. In the end, regardless of the result, we're still massively proud.. and we still dream. Bring on the World Cup! Experiencing these games like this.. it's the thrill of a lifetime.

text: Lewis Port to be clear and accurate, it’s worth understanding the origins or the term “it’s coming home” which to many outside of England may seem conceited, in fact it is not. It’s not about winning, although it has come to mean this recently, it’s mostly about the origins of the game itself and for once, being proud that England could prove itself a worth competitor in the game, which I believe (despite its loss) it has. I’d say that no ones tears are satisfying as that would be condoning sadness and hurt, for which I believe you are not doing, and am I glad we lost? No of course not. Do I believe we lost fairly, well yes of course. Us Brits are good losers after all. But we will win again once our team is of age!

It's laughable that not a single person here acknowledges the obvious rule book infringement—no fewer than 7 French players brazenly storm onto the pitch while the ball remains in play. Such a contravention is without question, a punishable offence, warranting a free kick for the opposing side.
Were the culprits in question Argentina, the outcry would be deafening, with cries of "rigged" echoing relentlessly through these very comments. But, of course, the narrative shifts when the team in question happens to be one graced by Messi’s presence, yeah? 😂😂

From this Englishman, thank you so much Croatia for being the ones to finally knock us out the World Cup and end this madness! There was no thought more horrific than us potentially winning this horrible tournament of a horrible game, organised by the fucking Mafia (FIFA)! Od ovog Engleza, toliko vam zahvaljujemo što ste nas konačno napali Svjetski kup i okončali ovu ludost! text:
I will give you my perspective and some reasons that the rest of the world seems to 
disfavour you.

– Bad reputation abroad for causing trouble. English fans have a reputation of being drunk, 
obnoxious and violent whilst abroad.
– Perceived arrogance that Football belongs to England. “It’s coming home” and all that. 
As a “big” footballing nation, you’ve only ever won anything when the WC was played here. 
Compare to Italy, Brazil, Spain, Germany, Argentina, France who have all won multiple 
trohpies.
– Sore losers and bad winners.
– British media. The Sun and the Daily Mail and Express are the main culprits.
– Generally perceived as quite a xenophobic nation – it’s rare for English footballers 
move abroad to other leagues. It’s even rarer for – English people to make any attempt 
at learning another language. Not helped by Brexit.
– The idea that England play football the way it’s meant to be played. You don’t. 
For the longest time you played 442 long ball which most decent teams never played.
– English players don’t dive, cheat or steal, whilst foreigners do everything and 
anything to win. 
You do dive cheat and steal. Alan Shearer saying otherwise doesn’t change the fact that 
Ashley Young, Delle Alli et al all do it. Maguire is the latest culprit.

I’ve probably missed something, but you get the general gist.

Some of you will probably see red when you read this and have one sentence going over 
and over in your head: “If you don’t like it leave!”. No. I do like it here, 
so I will stay ??

text:
There are two main points
1) If you raised the flag, some(or all) players stop, even if striker makes the shot maybe defenders didn't try anymore. So, it's more fair if everyone keeps on playing and later we see if the goal is legal or not.
2) It's not about all the calls, it's about very tight calls. When they are unsure linesmen tend to raise the flag more often than not. Because if you stop the attack by mistake it's just an attack, maybe they couldn't score anyway, but if you don't raise the flag when it's offside and they score it's illegal goal which counts. So, they want to stop that bad tendency as well.

text: This World Cup won't change anything in relation to the Messi vs Ronaldo debate, unless either one wins it & that ain't happening... Back the 2014 World Cup, the roles where reversed in the opening group games...Messi was scoring & playing really well & getting Argentina to the knock out stages, while Ronaldo struggled & Portugal got eliminated in the group stages...This World Cup it's the reverse. Ronaldo scoring & Messi struggling , with Argentina facing elimination at the group stages... Ultimately, people are gonna have their favorite player & who they consider the GOAT... There isn't a scientific objective measuring scale to prove once & for all, who is the GOAT...That's why before the millennium, it was ongoing between Pele & Maradona fans as to who, was the GOAT  & also, Di Stefano & Cruyff was in that discussion... Since 2000, Messi & Ronaldo have been added to that discussion...Like i said, there isn't an "objective" scientific method to decide this... It's like saying, who's the greatest between;The Beatles, James Brown, Jimi Hendrix, The Rolling Stones, Pink Floyd, Led Zeppelin, Stevie Wonder, Bob Marley, Michael Jackson, Prince... It's ultimately, all subjective.

text:
The Portugal - Spain, Argentina - Iceland games really highlight the differences between Ronaldo and Messi.

Messi, against World Cup newbies and International minnows is unable to rise to the occasion. He’s surrounded by other truly world class players, starting alongside Di Maria, Aguero and Mascherano from the beginning. However he failed. He couldn’t lead his team, he isn’t a motivator of players around them and he isn’t leading by example. This isn’t even talking about missing a penalty which probably would have won the game.

Ronaldo however is a very patriotic guy and he works just as hard, if not harder for Portugal, as he does for Real. He plays against one of the top international sides in the world, gets a hat trick, holds his nerve for the penalty and was at the back defending corners and crosses, as much as he was up in the box looking to score. He does this when he’s surrounded by truly substandard players. On paper, the Argentina team is well ahead of Portugal, but Ronaldo was the deciding factor.

Messi probably technically a better player than Ronaldo, his close control is probably better, however he offers so much more that Messi doesn’t.

Ronaldo is the GOAT.

text:
Good video, as ever.

VAR is a necessity given a combination of increasing pace at which the game is played and incompetence bordering on corruption on the part of certain officials. What's not immediately apparent are the longer-term effects. One of the implications is an easier time for the attacker once in the penalty area as defenders will go to greater lengths to avoid contact. Defanged defenders and emboldened attackers. I imagine a more intelligent intra-penalty-area defender evolving from this and that the last line will emphasise keeping attackers out of the penalty area. Some referees will look upon it as an embarrassing crutch, but even in the few World Cup™ matches already played, I detect a propensity to referees clamping down harder on infringements within the penalty area as though trying to prove they can cope just fine without the technological aid. The number of Russia 2018 matches played thus far makes for a measly sample, but I found it interesting that some assistant referees appeared to ignore some offsides because they didn't result in scoring opportunities. VAR is here to stay, but it's formal adoption will continue to face resistance. Kudos to Collina and his team for reducing the delay to decisions, but an effective doubling of the number of officiators per match seems much.

On a related note, VAR will certainly put money in pockets.

text: I thought VAR was terrible. A record number of penalties were awarded in this World Cup, and I don't necessarily think that's a good thing. More penalties awarded means less goals in open play, and this World Cup is proof of that. The VAR decision in the Grand Final most certainly ruined what was shaping up to be an all time classic. VAR can be helpful, but more often than not it instils doubt, indecision and hesitance in the minds of the referees, rendering them impotent.
author: @joe99173122

text: That's fair enough, but if there's anything that needs to be improved in football, it is eradicating the blight of diving and fake injuries. Instead of game changing and devastating penalties for an accidental brush of a ball on someone's hand, imagine a world where Neymar is held accountable for his bullshit, and free kicks aren't awarded to people who incessantly milk them. If you're going to interrupt a game and introduce technology anyway, why not address the REAL problem while you're at it?

text:
Admit that FIFA has always been corrupt since it's inception but mainly focus on Russia, Qatar, and South Africa. Basically everyone who's ever hosted should be treated with suspicion but no... these two are the worst.

Agree that Russia and Qatar being authoritarian and with deep pockets had undue advantage over other nations but on the same breath claim that other Western nations should have hosted since they had resources and infrastructure to do so hence an unfair advantage if those were the only criteria to be considered. Seems to me like chances of a country as small as mine hosting the World Cup are next to zero unless we can also buy our way in. If it's called a World Cup why does it matter how many football fans are in the country? Shouldn't the sport be uniting the world, promoting the sport to all nations and benefiting all nations? There should in fact be a rule lowering your success rate if you've ever hosted the tournament.

Isn't it interesting how Western media is so entitled to everything?

text: Rigged isn't the right word, and you shouldn't only take this match to claim such things. But look at the whole tournament. We have to be honest here; Argentina did get more decisions in their favor than other teams. Was it rigged? No, but it could have been influenced. Take Qatar; how did they get the World Cup in the first place? We all know how... so would it be that strange if they tried to "push" Argentina for the win? Especially if you knew beforehand it would probably be Messi's last chance to win it. The thing with football is, it's not a sport with clear-cut rules.  A lot of times, it's how the referee and VAR interpret the situation. So, sadly, football, in my eyes, will never be a completely fair sport. We have all seen really shady decisions that left us with irritated feelings, or however you react to them. Not even talking about Argentina alone, but about the sport as a whole. Anyway, do I think it was rigged? No, but I wouldn't be surprised if they tried to push for Argentina to win.

text:
A game being rigged is like influencing the odds, in other words, influencing the people evaluating how to pass mistakes. To a strong team like Argentina, that is like a almost guarantee that they can just bypass rules and regulations. Similar for the last Spain EC. Somehow for specific groups there are just rule bending priviliges. Not always, but in some games it is extremely noticeable. Yes, football is rigged, and Fifa is ultra famous for being corrupt. Why would anyone even defend something else?

Saying that people need proof for this just shows that you do not understand how football business and general law works. Even more, most of the comments here are also probably by children understanding very little about the actual dynamics. 

Again, the cup being rigged means: there is influence on how mistakes are being evaluated, either by referee bias or by corruption. This influences the game, given that a team is good, also maximizes the chances of winning. Not sure why people here get it wrong

text:
My friend,for someone who loves and follows Football,at least for the last 20 years,knows very well that Messi ( and  Barcelona)has been FIFA and UEFA "Protégé.
It's a fact of life, because there are no such thing as coincidences.
Argentina has the new World Cup Record,for the team with more penalties awarded,5 penalties in 7 games.
If Messi was awarded with the 2nd yellow card,most likely wouldn't be present on the final.
And many other "small" details, that put together can make all the difference between winning or  being the "other" team.
PS: why did Messi won other Ballon D'or in 2023...???!!
Because he won the 2022 World Cup...??!!
Because if winning a World Cup it's enough to be awarded with the Ballon D'or,i can say the name of 3 Argentina players who also Won the same World Cup,who did had a much more Successfull  season than Lionel Messi.
Not to mention other players,from other countries that were also more ( by far) Successfull than Messi on the same season,but didin't won a world Cup.
I'am a 63 years old Die Hard Football Fan,and always try to be FAIR ,even when concerning my Beloved National Team,and my Beloved "personal" Team .
Always try to see the Football as an Honest and Fair game, where the best is the one that Deserves to Win.
Unfortunably, because of some Greedy, Dishonest and Immoral people, Football also have been Corrupted to the core.
Even with those 2 POS criminals, Blatter and Platini out of the picture,the seeds of Corruption that those 2 Leeches planted on FIFA and UEFA,are still growing Strong and in some cases in a Disgusting Shameless way.
Unfortunably, since players started to be "Bought" by dozens an hundreds of Millions €, Football nowadays it's another huge Profitable business,than the Real and Greatest Sport on Earth.

text: I believe it was definitely a bust. The Mexican people have grown tired of priding themselves on good quality. We know the quality is there. Not to the standards of say a Germany or Spain, but it’s still good enough to go toe to toe with any team and not make it easy. But yet, It’s 7x proving to the world we’re no more than a round of 16 team. So yes, 100% it’s a disappointment. The problem for me has always been having an incompetent coach. Osorio was never great no matter how you put it. When you have the players that you have in bench and you opt for 40yr old to start when he shouldn’t even been there to begin with, is a huge problem. He gassed out & was subbed out immediately. The problem is idiot decision making &favoritism. He continued to give huge mins to a LB/RB player who can’t cross or shoot to save his life & play him as a RW? You don’t utilize Jesus corona, arguably most talented winger bar Lozano. There was a lack of talent in striker position. Your wingers are the type to cut in & score. Against Brazil he randomly put vela (Left footer) on the left wing, and Lozano (right footer) on the right wing as if he was this master tactician trying to confuse Brazil. There was no one to cross to, and when open, very uncomfortable to shoot. Make no mistake, Joan dos Santos liking that tweet showing dissatisfaction w/ the line up, was not accidental

Belgium simply decided that it's close enough of gambling (especially on how it affects peoples emotionally) to include it in there. As for the prison years, well it's because you're not allowed to run gambling business without proper licenses, so as soon as lootboxes are recognises as a form of gambling, any game with lootboxes is a shady and unauthorised online gambling business. Ozil, khedira, and Mueller were practically nonexistent. Werner had his moments but was ultimately poor. Kimmich and Boateng I believe were more a symptom of lows overall game plan, but it does look like Boatengs constant injuries are starting to show. We have a lot of improving to do until the next euro and world cup, but in all honesty with this much young talent I'm not really too worried about it.

text: The most aerodynamic thing is a teardrop, the spherical ball is definitely not very aerodynamic. The issues with it relate to the fact that the drag and flows behind the ball are less turbulent than those of its predecessors, because there are less seams and it has a smoother surface it’s both quicker through the air and it’s stability is less predictable. Its direction is harder to judge because the airflow can detach with an unpredictable outcome. It’s counterintuitive that a rough and less perfect ball is easier to control and to predict but ‘perfect’ airflow is very quick to become unbalanced but messy airflow that’s slower to change is easier for players to deal with.
